  "prompt": "How does a hydraulic brake work? Describe in brief",
  "response": "A hydraulic brake system uses fluid to transfer the force applied by the driver\u2019s brake pedal to the wheels, enabling effective stopping power. When the brake pedal is pressed, it activates a master cylinder that pressurizes brake fluid within the sealed system. This pressurized fluid travels through brake lines to each wheel\u2019s brake calipers (in disc brakes) or wheel cylinders (in drum brakes). The fluid pressure causes the brake pads or shoes to clamp against the brake discs or drums, creating friction that slows and stops the vehicle. Hydraulic brakes are favored for their smooth, reliable performance and even distribution of braking force across all wheels.",
